SOB 24: Produce a System of Multiple Devices that Communicate Wirelessly

Hardware

Arduino Uno
LDR Sensor
Ultrasonic Distance Sensor
Breadboard and connecting wires

Software

Arduino IDE
Python
PyCharm
Blynk Cloud Platform
Blynk API Library
Serial Communication

Cloud Services

Blynk IoT Dashboard
Blynk Virtual Pins (V0 and V1)

Project Overview

This project extends the IoT system developed in SOB 22 and SOB 23 by
 connecting the physical sensors to an Internet-based cloud platform.

The Arduino Uno reads data from:

An LDR sensor measuring light intensity.
An ultrasonic sensor measuring distance.

The sensor values are transmitted to a Python application through serial
 communication. The Python script then processes the data and publishes the
  latest sensor readings to the Blynk cloud platform using the Blynk API.

This allows the sensor data to be monitored remotely using an online dashboard,
 effectively transforming the project into a complete Internet of Things (IoT) system.

System Architecture

LDR Sensor
      \
       \
        Arduino Uno
       /
Ultrasonic Sensor

        |
        | Serial Communication
        v

      Python Script

        |
        | Blynk API
        v

    Blynk Cloud

        |
        v

 Blynk Dashboard

Arduino Program

The Arduino performs two primary tasks:

Read LDR Sensor
int lightValue = analogRead(LDR_PIN);


This collects the current light intensity level.

Read Ultrasonic Sensor
float distance = duration * 0.034 / 2;


This calculates the distance between the sensor and nearby objects.

Send Data to Python
Serial.print("LDR:");
Serial.print(lightValue);

Serial.print(",Distance:");
Serial.println(distance);


The Arduino continuously sends sensor data through the serial connection.

Python Program

The Python application acts as the bridge between the Arduino and the cloud.

Imported Libraries
import serial
import time
import BlynkLib

Establish Arduino Connection
arduino = serial.Serial(
    port="COM3",
    baudrate=9600,
    timeout=1
)


Python continuously listens for incoming Arduino sensor data.

Establish Blynk Connection
blynk = BlynkLib.Blynk(BLYNK_AUTH)


The Blynk authentication token connects the application to the online Blynk
 cloud platform.

Receiving and Processing Data

Python receives incoming measurements:

data = arduino.readline().decode().strip()


The values are separated and stored:

ldr_value = int(values[0])
distance_value = float(values[1])


This ensures the data is correctly interpreted before being uploaded.

Publishing Data to Blynk

LDR Sensor
blynk.virtual_write(
    0,
    ldr_value
)


Published on:

Virtual Pin V0

Ultrasonic Sensor

blynk.virtual_write(
    1,
    distance_value
)


Published on:

Virtual Pin V1

Blynk Dashboard Configuration

According to the dashboard screenshot:

Widget 1

LDR Value Gauge

Virtual Pin: V0
Range: 0 - 1023


Displays real-time light readings from the LDR sensor.

Widget 2

Distance Gauge

Virtual Pin: V1
Range: 0 - 400


Displays real-time distance measurements from the ultrasonic sensor.

Widget 3

Live Data Chart

The chart visualizes:

LDR readings over time
Distance readings over time

allowing sensor activity to be monitored remotely through the cloud.

Example Analysis of Dashboard

LDR Gauge

Current reading approximately: 436

This indicates the LDR is detecting a moderate light level.

Distance Gauge

Current reading approximately: 9.23

This indicates that an object was positioned very close to the ultrasonic sensor
 during testing.

Real-Time Graph

The graph displays continuous updates from both sensors.

The spikes visible in the graph correspond to environmental changes such as:

Covering or uncovering the LDR sensor.
Moving a hand closer to or farther from the ultrasonic sensor.

This confirms successful cloud-based monitoring and visualization.

Practical Demonstration

A classroom demonstration was performed.

Ultrasonic Sensor Test

When a hand was moved in front of the ultrasonic sensor:

Distance values decreased.
The Blynk dashboard updated immediately.
The graph reflected the change in real time.

LDR Sensor Test

When the LDR sensor was covered:

Light readings changed significantly.
New values appeared on the dashboard gauges.
The graph updated automatically.

This demonstrated successful acquisition, transmission, cloud publishing,
 and visualization of sensor data.

Explanation

This project extends the IoT solution developed in SOB 22 and SOB 23 by
 integrating the Blynk cloud platform. Data collected from an LDR sensor
  and an ultrasonic sensor is transmitted from the Arduino Uno to a Python
   application through serial communication. Python processes the readings
    and uses the Blynk API to publish the latest values to virtual pins V0 and V1.
     The Blynk dashboard displays the sensor readings using gauges and a
     live graph, allowing remote monitoring of environmental data.
      Testing confirmed that changes in light intensity and distance measurements
       were reflected instantly on the online dashboard.